* Readme file
/*
This sample race is for a 5 km road race. 

The race has a single start.

The race has the following events(mats): a GunStart and a ChipStart, an Announce, and a Finish.


We recommend using the Priority to group your listing files.
You may also use different colors to differentiate the functionality of the different listing files.

All the files follow the best practice recommendation.


We recommend starting each listing file with a short comment describing its purposes.


Unregistered (bandit) runner number
------------------------------------
When a finish is recorded for a bib or chip number that is not in the entries
database, RunScore assigns it to a special "unregistered" runner (also called the
bandit). This lets you keep the result without stopping to register the runner
during the race.

RunScore decides which number to use in the following order. Each step, when set,
overrides the one before it:

    1. A built-in default of 0.
    2. The unregistered runner number from your RunScore profile -- your default
       for every race.
    3. The "unregistered number" setting in this race's Entries.INI, which applies
       to this race only and takes precedence over the profile.

This 5K race sets the value in Entries.INI:

    unregistered number 20000

so the unregistered runner is identified by bib 20000 in this race.

A related Entries.INI setting controls what happens to a number that is read but
not found in the database:

    Not found added     yes

With "Not found added" set to yes, an unknown bib/chip is added to the database as
a new entry (with no name) instead of being assigned to the unregistered runner;
set it to no to record the result against the unregistered runner without creating
a new entry.

To change the default, edit the "unregistered number" value in this race's
Entries.INI (this race only), or change the "Unregistered runner number" field in
Tools > Preferences (applies to new races).
*/